{
  "text": "Although there has been a recent report in which the growth of haemozoin crystals in individual parasites has been observed through the blood-cycle using spinning-disk confocal microscopy [CITATION_1] , the growth of haemozoin in the organism does not provide direct insight into mechanism. This is because the rate of formation in the parasite will reflect rates of Hb uptake from the red blood cell cytoplasm, rate of Hb proteolysis as well as rate of haemozoin formation. Given that the concentration of nonhaemozoin haem in mature trophozoites cannot be detected by M\u00f6ssbauer spectroscopy, thus representing less than 5% of iron present in the parasite [CITATION_2] , it would seem likely that uptake and digestion of haemoglobin are probably rate limiting. As a result, what we know of the kinetics and mechanism of haemozoin formation arises from biomimetic studies of \uf062-haematin formation.",
  "citation_candidates": [
